","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/5/17/1337285260832/Alexis-Tsipras-the-leader-003.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Guardian","photographer":"Martin Godwin","altText":"Alexis Tsipras, the leader of Syriza","height":"84","credit":"Martin Godwin/Guardian","caption":"Alexis Tsipras, the leader of Syriza, continues to reject the Greek government's EU-mandated austerity deal. Photograph: Martin Godwin for the Guardian","width":"140"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Spanish crisis hits European stock markets","webPublicationDate":"2012-05-18T12:43:23Z","sectionName":"Business","sectionId":"business","id":"business/2012/may/18/spanish-crisis-hits-european-stock-markets","fields":{"standfirst":"• FTSE 100 index falls to lowest level since November<br />• Claim that contingency plan is in place for Greek euro exit","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2013-07-01T06:30:47Z","body":"<p>Global stock markets suffered further losses on Friday as Spain fought to avoid being sucked deeper into the escalating crisis that threatens to push Greece out of the eurozone.</p><p>In London the FTSE 100 index of leading UK companies shed another 70 points to close to its lowest level since last November, after a rout in Asian markets knocked almost 3% off the Japanese Nikkei. The FTSE 100 has now shed 11% since mid-March, as fears over Greece leaving the euro have intensified. Almost £80bn has been knocked off its value in the last week.</p><p>Greece remained centre-stage, after the Athens goverment stated that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2012/may/18/eurozone-crisis-stock-markets-greece-spain#block-32\" title=\"\">German chancellor Angela Merkel had suggested that the Greeks hold a referendum on their membership of the eurozone</a>. The report was swiftly denied by Berlin.</p><p>EU officials also denied having a secret plan for a Greek euro-exit, after EU trade commissioner Karel De Gucht told a Dutch newspaper that European authorities had drawn up contingency measures to protect the euro in the event of Greece leaving the single currency. A European commission spokesman later denied that an emergency plan was under way, insisting: \"We are concentrating all our efforts on supporting Greece and keeping it in the eurozone.\"</p><p>On Thursday night, Fitch downgraded its credit rating on Greece, saying there was a higher risk that it leaves the single currency after June's general election.</p><p>The selloff was also prompted by the news late on Thursday that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/may/17/spain-denies-bankia-customers-rushing-to-withdraw\" title=\"\">rating agency Moody's had slashed its rating on 16 Spanish banks</a>. Santander was hit with a three-notch downgrade, with its British arm downgraded one notch. Moody's blamed the sweeping downgrade on the weakening Spanish economy, and the Madrid government's own deteriorating credit-worthiness.</p><p>Santander UK insisted that the move would not affect its growth plans, adding that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2012/may/18/santander-is-your-money-safe\" title=\"\">customers should remain confident</a> that it was well capitalised despite the problems in Spain. In another blow to the Spanish economy, the percentage of impaired bank debts rose to its highest level since 1994.</p><p>The Spanish government announced that it will name two independent auditors on Monday to conduct stress tests to see whether its banks are strong enough. City analyst Nicholas Spiro, of Spiro Sovereign Strategy, warned that Spain was \"treading on very thin ice\".</p><p>\"The increasing risk of a Greek exit from the eurozone is putting even more pressure on Spanish bond yields as 'break-up contagion' starts to take hold. The downgrades are part of a drip-feed of dire economic and financial news out of Spain,\" Spiro said.</p><p>Traders in the City were in gloomy mood, despite the excitement of the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2012/may/18/facebook-ipo-stock-market-live\" title=\"\">impending Facebook flotation</a>.</p><p>\"The ugly prospect of bank runs appears to be spreading over Europe, rumours having hit Spanish banks yesterday to complement those heard about Greece earlier in the week,\" said David Jones of IG Index.</p><p>The FTSE 100 ended 70 points lower, or 1.33% down, at 5267. The German DAX finished 0.6% lower, while the Nikkei closed 2.99% at 8611.31. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones index was down 57 points, or 0.46% lower, at 12385 in afternoon trading.</p>","headline":"Spanish crisis hits European stock markets","trailText":"Stock markets across Europe and Asia suffered further losses on Friday as Spain fought to avoid being sucked deeper into the escalating crisis that threatens to push Greece out of the eurozone","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/37yxb","wordcount":"499","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"390330542","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6194560","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Graeme Wearden","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-05-19T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1747451","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-05-21T12:43:23Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2012/may/18/spanish-crisis-hits-european-stock-markets","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/business/2012/may/18/spanish-crisis-hits-european-stock-markets","tags":[{"id":"business/debt-crisis","webTitle":"Eurozone crisis","references":[],"type":"keyword","sectionId":"business","sectionName":"Business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/debt-crisis","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/business/debt-crisis"},{"id":"business/banking","webTitle":"Banking","references":[],"type":"keyword","sectionId":"business","